<DOC><DOCNO> DOE2-35-0018 </DOCNO><TEXT>The radioactive fallout from the Chernobyl accident fell on many countrieswithout consideration of national or political frontiers. Countries inthe East and West were affected. One consequence on this was a wave ofprotests and rallies across both East and West, in Italy, in Germany,in Yugoslavia, Poland and Czechoslovakia. For many, the Chernobyl accidentchanged their lives and affected their livelihoods. The broad equivalenceof Eastern and Western governmental and popular responses to the accidentis discussed. First, the East European and Soviet peace and ecology groupsand their response to the Chernobyl accident are considered. The Westernpeace movements are explained, especially their indifference or reticencetowards Eastern Europe. In particular the situation in Britain is discussed.(U.K.).</TEXT></DOC>